description.value:
Painting in water based pigment on printed Italian military paper depicting the flight into Egypt. Mary rides a donkey with the infant Christ on her lap, to the left is Salome and the the right, leading the donkey, is Joseph. Joseph carries a stick to which two gourds are attached. Above the holy family are two angels.

Verso; Salome, Joseph and Mary are shown sleeping while the infant Christ suckles, his eyes open. Above is an angel who points down to Joseph.
Framed with a paper mount.

description.value: Fragmentary portrait of a woman in tempera on wood, inscribed in Greek 'Serapi[as]': only the left edge of the panel is preserved with sand and mastic on the back. Visible are the proper right ear, the lower lid and part of the pupil of the right eye, the nose from bridge to nostril and part of both cheeks. In her pierced ear the woman wears a gold hoop earring threaded with pearls, of which two are visible.    Above them two corkscrew locks of black hair hang in front of the ear. The flesh is warmly tinted in tones of cream, apricot and rose pink with an ochre-green shadow by the nose. The nostrils are drawn in dark red.

description.value: A small section of the wooden panel from a naos: elaborately inlaid in mosaic and monochrome glass and gilded. The inlays described here, all monochrome, are in two blocks of plaster, apparently not in their original order.    The larger group consists of the remains of a panel representing a flying falcon in dark-blue and  light  turquoise-blue glass. Some of the feathers are tipped with red. Scattered traces of gold-leaf. Also set into this plaster are two shaped pieces in dark-blue glass. The smaller group appears to be from the lower area of the panel, that section so frequently decorated with palace-facade panelling. The uppermost register is a series of vertical rectangles in opaque dark-blue glass alternating with the aa-sign hieroglyph in light turquoise-blue glass. Below is a register of the nb-sign hieroglyph in dark-blue glass. In the lowest register are groups of three horizontal rectangles in opaque red and light turquoise-blue glass. All  glass surfaces are  filmed.
